the way I understand it, and very simplified:

– They believe that Al-Hakim Bi Amr-Allah, the 16th Ismaili Shia Imam & 6th Fatimid Caliph, is actually the final reincarnation / manifestation of Allah (???) and that he did not actually die, but went into occultation.

– This belief was first expressed by a guy called Hamza ibn Ali, a Persian who lived in the 11th century in Cairo, and even Al-Hakim himself made fun of this belief.

– This guy, Hamza, wrote some letters, stating that Al-Hakim will eventually come back and spread 'Druze wisdom' throughout the world. These letters are called the 'Epistles of Wisdom'.

– Some additional letters were written by another guy called Baha Al-Din Al-Muqtana, nobody knows anything about him except that he was born in Syria and was likely a Christian. He announced his retirement and disappeared to a random unknown place.

– The Druze believe that Plato, Socrates and other Greek philosophers were actually Prophets, and they generally believe in astrology and other stuff.

– They believe it's forbidden to share their beliefs with 'ignorants' (those who are non-religious Druze)

And many more things.

Reading poetry, as much as writing it, is path toward a greater cultivation and knowledge of the self. That's what I believe and how I derive enjoyment from it, at least.

>>213026812
>It's not even that I don't like the language, because I do, but I'm just not keen on it right now; don't have the passion for it.

You unlock "passion" once you make enough progress to feel good about what you're doing. This switcharoo shit is the beginner's curse, it only happens to people that overthink at the start and haven't put enough time into the hobby to get any meaningful results. Learn the top 1000 most common words, read one (1) graded reader from start to finish, understand a TL video from start to finish, get through one movie or tv show episode while doing lookups, put 100 hours of effort into your TL, achieve any kind of meaningful milestone and you will feel good about it. And once you feel good about it, you realize you can put in some more work and experience it again.
